Amy,<br><br>
The Wall is a source of great strength for me, even though it hurts like hell to visit it. Those who view it as a mark of shame are right in one respect, but we need more. What better way to keep reminding self serving little zeros at the top that they really screwed up, and we don't like it.<br><br>
If you study Washington carefully, you will find that it is a grandiose monument to patriotism. It can humble you in the light of great words and deeds of the past, and can make you proud. The Lincoln Memorial, in particular, reminds me of that. Washington is also a grandiose monument to the folly of humanity. Many of the functional government buildings imitate greatness, but are really full of small minded, self serving, narrowly focused people who can't get out of their own way, much less do anyone any good. I may be accused of cynicism, but as a Vietnam Veteran, I have a right to be.<br><br>
I have always found that those who bear the mark of shame are the ones who complain the loudest.<br><br>
The Wall honors those who gave their lives for this country. It should matter not for what cause. They were sent to Vietnam by and for the country, and it is only fitting that they be honored for their ultimate sacrifice. We, the living, must keep their memory alive.<br><br>
Art 
